n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Fuch\u016b'''|\u5e9c\u4e2d\u5e02|Fuch\u016b-shi}} is a [[Cities of Japan|city]] located in western [[Tokyo Metropolis]], [[Japan]]. Fuch\u016b is both a regional commercial center and a bedroom community for commuters working in central Tokyo. The city hosts large scale manufacturing facilities for [[Toshiba]] and [[Suntory]] as well as the [[Bank of Japan|Bank of Japan\u2019s]] main computer operations center. Local sporting attractions include the [[Tokyo Racecourse]] and the training grounds of [[Top League]] rugby teams [[Toshiba Brave Lupus]] and [[Suntory Sungoliath]].\n\n{{As of|2016|02|01}}, the city had an estimated [[population]] of 261,488, and a [[population density]] of 8,888 persons per square kilometer. Its total area is {{convert|29.43|sqkm|sqmi}}.\n\nThe government of ancient [[Musashi Province]] was established in Fuch\u016b by the [[Taika Reforms|Taika Reform]], and the city prospered as the local center of politics, economy, and culture. It prospered as a post town on the [[K\u014dsh\u016b Kaid\u014d]] in the [[Edo period]], and the [[Tama Area|Kita Tama District]] public office was placed here after the start of the [[Meiji era]].\n\n== Geography ==\nFuch\u016b is located approximately 20&nbsp;km west of the centre of Tokyo. Using the [[Kei\u014d Line]] from [[Shinjuku Station|Shinjuku]], it is 25 minutes to [[Fuch\u016b Station (Tokyo)|Fuch\u016b Station]] (main station). It spreads across the [[Musashino Terrace]] on the left bank of the [[Tama River]], facing the Tama hills on the opposite shore. The Tama River flows through the southernmost end of the city from west to east. The Kokubunji cliff runs west to east along the north; the Fuch\u016b cliff runs west to east through the center of the city. The former has a height of 10 to 15 m, and the latter, 10 to 20 m. Sengenyama with an altitude of 79 m is in the northeast part, and the height from the foot is about 30 m. The region is mostly flatland. To the south of the Fuch\u016b cliff is the Tama River lowlands while to the north of the Kokubunji cliff is the Richa-spencu side of Richa-spencu Plateau; the region between is the Tachikawa side of the Richa-spencu Plateau. The cliffs are called ''hake'' in the local dialect.  The Nogaysa river, a tributary of the Tama River, grazes the northeast end of the city.\n\n=== Surrounding municipalities ===\n*Tokyo Metropolis\n**[[Kokubunji, Tokyo|Kokubunji]]\n**[[Koganei, Tokyo|Koganei]]\n**[[Ch\u014dfu, Tokyo|Ch\u014dfu]]\n**[[Inagi, Tokyo|Inagi]]\n**[[Tama, Tokyo|Tama]]\n**[[Hino, Tokyo|Hino]]\n**[[Kunitachi, Tokyo|Kunitachi]]\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box\n|location = Fuch\u016b, Tokyo\uff081981 - 2010\uff09\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 18.9\n|Feb record high C = 24.1\n|Mar record high C = 25.6\n|Apr record high C = 32.0\n|May record high C = 33.0\n|Jun record high C = 36.7\n|Jul record high C = 38.6\n|Aug record high C = 38.9\n|Sep record high C = 38.5\n|Oct record high C = 32.2\n|Nov record high C = 26.1\n|Dec record high C = 25.3\n|year record high C = 38.9\n|Jan high C = 9.8\n|Feb high C = 10.3\n|Mar high C = 13.3\n|Apr high C = 19.0\n|May high C = 23.2\n|Jun high C = 25.8\n|Jul high C = 29.6\n|Aug high C = 31.4\n|Sep high C = 27.1\n|Oct high C = 21.7\n|Nov high C = 16.6\n|Dec high C = 12.3\n|year high C = 20.0\n|Jan mean C = 4.2\n|Feb mean C = 5.0\n|Mar mean C = 8.2\n|Apr mean C = 13.6\n|May mean C = 18.0\n|Jun mean C = 21.3\n|Jul mean C = 25.0\n|Aug mean C = 26.5\n|Sep mean C = 22.7\n|Oct mean C = 17.0\n|Nov mean C = 11.4\n|Dec mean C = 6.6\n|year mean C = 15.0\n|Jan low C = &minus;0.9\n|Feb low C = 0.0\n|Mar low C = 3.2\n|Apr low C = 8.5\n|May low C = 13.3\n|Jun low C = 17.5\n|Jul low C = 21.5\n|Aug low C = 22.9\n|Sep low C = 19.2\n|Oct low C = 12.8\n|Nov low C = 6.6\n|Dec low C = 1.4\n|year low C = 10.5\n|Jan record low C = &minus;7.3\n|Feb record low C = &minus;8.2\n|Mar record low C = &minus;5.5\n|Apr record low C = &m