{"title_page": "2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season", "text_new": "{{short description|87th season in franchise history}}\n{{Infobox NFL season\n| team            = Pittsburgh Steelers\n| logo            = \n| year            = 2019\n| record          = 8\u20138\n| division_place  = 2nd [[AFC North]]\n| coach           = [[Mike Tomlin]]\n| general manager = [[Kevin Colbert]]\n| owner           = [[Rooney family|The Rooney Family]]\n| stadium         = [[Heinz Field]]\n| pro bowlers     = {{Collapsible list\n|title = 6\n|1 = OG [[David DeCastro]]\n|2 = FS [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]]\n|3 = CB [[Joe Haden]]\n|4 = DT [[Cameron Heyward]]\n|5 = C [[Maurkice Pouncey]]\n|6 = OLB [[T. J. Watt]]}}\n| AP All-pros = {{Collapsible list\n|title = 5\n|1 = FS [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]] ''(1st team)''\n|2 = DT [[Cameron Heyward]]\n''(1st team)''\n|3 = PR [[Diontae Johnson]]\n''(2nd team)''\n|4 = EDGE [[T. J. Watt]]\n''(1st team)''\n|5 = LB [[T. J. Watt]]\n''(2nd team)''\n}}\n| playoffs        = ''Did not qualify''\n| MVP = [[T. J. Watt]]\n| ROY = [[Devin Bush Jr.]]\n| uniform         = Pittsb steelers uniforms17.png \n| shortnavlink    = Steelers seasons\n}}\nThe [[2019 NFL season|2019 season]] was the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]' 87th as a professional sports franchise and as a member of the [[National Football League]]. It marked the 20th season under leadership of general manager [[Kevin Colbert]] and the 13th under [[List of Pittsburgh Steelers head coaches|head coach]] [[Mike Tomlin]].  The team failed to improve upon its 9\u20136\u20131 record from [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2018]] following a Week 16 loss to the [[2019 New York Jets season|New York Jets]].\n\nFor the first time since [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2013]], they started the season with a 1\u20134 record through Week 5, which included a humiliating 33\u20133 blowout loss to the defending [[Super Bowl LIII|Super Bowl]] champion [[2019 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]], and an injury to [[Ben Roethlisberger]] the very next game. However, they went on to win seven out of their next eight games to sit in Week 14 of the season with a 8\u20135 record before they ended up losing three consecutive important games to end the 2019 season with an 8\u20138 record. They also tied for their worst record ([[2006 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2006]] (they were defending Super Bowl Champions), 2012, 2013) since the 2003 season. \n\nFor the first time since the [[2012 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2012]] and 2013 seasons, they were mathematically eliminated from postseason contention for the second consecutive year after a 28\u201310 loss to the [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] coupled with the [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] defeating the [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] 35\u201314 for the final AFC Wild Card spot in Week 17.\n{{TOClimit|3}}\n\n==Roster moves==\nSeveral players who played significant roles in the Steelers' recent success did not return for 2019. Among the departed were:\n*Offensive tackle [[Marcus Gilbert (American football)| Marcus Gilbert]], traded to the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on March 8, 2019 for the Cardinals compensatory 6th round pick, used on [[Ulysees Gilbert III]].\n*Wide receiver [[Antonio Brown]], traded to the [[Oakland Raiders]] on March 9, 2019 for the Raiders 3rd and 5th round picks in the [[2019 NFL Draft]], used to select [[Diontae Johnson]] and [[Zach Gentry]], respectively.\n*Running back [[Le'Veon Bell]], who signed with the [[New York Jets]] on March 13, 2019.\n*Tight end [[Jesse James (tight end)|Jesse James]], who signed with the [[Detroit Lions]] on March 14, 2019.\n\nSeveral of these moves were made in the name of eliminating \"distractions\", namely from Brown and Bell.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://steelerswire.usatoday.com/2019/04/28/steelers-hc-mike-tomlin-calls-roster-moves-a-cleansing/ |title=Steelers HC Mike Tomlin calls roster moves a 'cleansing' |last=Popejoy |first=Curt |date=April 28, 2019 |website=Steelers Wire |publisher=USA Today Sports |access-date=July 13, 2019 }}</ref> Brown had several clashes with the coaching staff, sports media and teammates (most notably [[Ben Roethlisberger]] and [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]]) and was subsequently benched in the Steelers season finale against the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], which led to Brown demanding a trade. Bell had been tagged with the [[franchise tag]] the previous two seasons and sat out the 2018 season; the Steelers opted not to tag him for a third time due to [[salary cap]] constraints as well as the emergence of fan favorite [[James Conner (American football)|James Conner]] and Bell subsequently signed with the Jets for less than what the Steelers had offered him. Gilbert was injured for much of 2018 and was made expendable due to the emergence of [[Matt Feiler]] in his spot. James, initially groomed to be the heir replacement to [[Heath Miller]], ultimately remained a backup after the Steelers traded for [[Vance McDonald]].\n\nIn addition to the players traded away and cut, [[Ryan Shazier]] remained out due to his 2017 spinal injury against the Bengals. After struggling to fill his role during the 2018 campaign, the Steelers addressed his long-term absence by going to the other side of the [[Michigan\u2013Ohio State football rivalry]] by trading up in the 2019 draft to draft [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] linebacker [[Devin Bush Jr.]] Shazier was subsequently placed on the reserve/PUP list for the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steelers place Shazier on PUP list|url=https://www.steelers.com/news/steelers-place-shazier-on-pup-list|author=Varley, Teresa|website=Steelers.com|date=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Draft===\n{{main|2019 NFL Draft}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| 2019 Pittsburgh Steelers Draft\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Round\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Selection\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Player\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Position\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| College\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Notes\n|-\n! [[List of Pittsburgh Steelers first-round draft picks|1]] || 10\n| [[Devin Bush Jr.|Devin Bush]] || [[Linebacker|ILB]] || [[2018 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] || from [[2019 Denver Broncos season|Denver]]\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| 3 || 66\n| [[Diontae Johnson]] || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] || [[2018 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]] || from [[Oakland Raiders|Oakland]]\n|-\n! 83\n| [[Justin Layne]] || [[Cornerback|CB]] || [[2018 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]] ||\n|-\n! 4 || 122\n| [[Benny Snell]] || [[Running Back|RB]] || [[2018 Kentucky Wildcats football team|Kentucky]] ||\n|-\n! 5 || 141\n| [[Zach Gentry]] || [[Tight End|TE]] || [[2018 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] || from [[Oakland Raiders|Oakland]]\n|-\n!rowspan=\"3\"| 6 || 175\n| [[Sutton Smith]] || [[Outside Linebacker|OLB]] || [[2018 Northern Illinois Huskies football team|Northern Illinois]] || from [[Oakland Raiders|Oakland]]\n|-\n!192\n| [[Isaiah Buggs]] || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[2018 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] ||\n|-\n! 207\n| [[Ulysees Gilbert III]] || [[Linebacker|ILB]] || [[2018 Akron Zips football team|Akron]] || from [[Arizona Cardinals|Arizona]]\n|-\n! 7 || 219\n| [[Derwin Gray (offensive lineman)|Derwin Gray]] || [[Offensive Tackle|OT]] || [[2018 Maryland Terrapins football team|Maryland]] || from [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay]]\n|}\n'''Notes'''\n\n*Pittsburgh traded their 2019 fifth-round selection to Oakland in exchange for wide receiver [[Ryan Switzer]] and Oakland's sixth-round selection.\n*Pittsburgh traded their 2019 seventh-round selection and wide receiver [[Sammie Coates]] to Cleveland in exchange for Cleveland's 2018 sixth-round selection that originally belonged to Pittsburgh.\n*Pittsburgh traded their 2018 sixth-round selection to Tampa Bay in exchange for their 2019 seventh-round selection and free safety [[J. J. Wilcox]].\n*Pittsburgh traded right tackle [[Marcus Gilbert (American football)|Marcus Gilbert]] to Arizona in exchange for a 2019 sixth-round compensatory selection.\n*Pittsburgh traded wide receiver [[Antonio Brown]] to Oakland in exchange for Oakland's third round selection and their fifth-round selection.\n\n===Undrafted free agents===\nAll [[Undrafted sportsperson|undrafted free agent]]s were signed after the [[2019 NFL draft]] concluded on April 26 unless otherwise noted.\n\n{|style=\"margin: 0.75em 0 0 0.5em\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#d9e9f9; border:1px solid #aaa; width:2em; text-align:center\"| \n| = Made Week 1 roster || \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Position\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Player\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| College\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Pittsburgh Steelers|year=2019|border=2}}\"| Notes\n|- \n| S || Dravon Askew-Henry || [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] || <!--NOTES-->\n|-\n| P || Ian Berryman || [[Western Carolina Catamounts football|Western Carolina]] || <!--NOTES-->\n|-\n| G || Garrett Brumfield || [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] || \n|-\n| DE || Greg Gilmore || [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] || Signed May 13\n|-\n| DE || Jay Hayes || [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] || <!--NOTES-->\n|-\n| QB || Devlin Hodges || [[Samford Bulldogs football|Samford]] || Signed May 13\n|-\n|style=\"background:#d9e9f9;| G ||style=\"background:#d9e9f9;| Fred Johnson ||style=\"background:#d9e9f9;| [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] ||style=\"background:#